        <h3><strong>2.5. Accessing Elements of a Matrix</strong><strong></strong></h3>
        <p>If we wanted to kwon the dimensions of a given matrix, we can ask what is the <strong><span style="color: #a35212ff;">shape</span></strong> of the matrix:</p>
        <p><span style="color: #2dc26b; font-size: 10pt;"><strong style="color: #197841ff;">In[1]:</strong></span></p>
        <pre><strong><span style="color: #0000ff;">import</span> numpy <span style="color: #0000ff;">as</span> np</strong><br /><strong>A = np.array([[1,2,3],[4,5,6]])<br />A.shape</strong></pre>
        <p><span style="color: #e03e2d; font-size: 10pt;"><strong style="color: #c83223ff;">Out[1]:</strong></span></p>
        <pre><strong>(2,3)</strong></pre>
        <p>To access elements in a matrix, we can specify the position of the element using squared brackets. Below are some examples</p>
        <p><span style="color: #2dc26b; font-size: 10pt;"><strong style="color: #197841ff;">In[1]:</strong></span></p>
        <pre><strong><span style="color: #0000ff;">import</span> numpy <span style="color: #0000ff;">as</span> np<br />A = np.array([[<span style="color: #806800ff;">11</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">12</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">13</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">14</span>],[<span style="color: #806800ff;">21</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">22</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">23</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">24</span>],[<span style="color: #806800ff;">31</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">32</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">33</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">34</span>]])</strong><br /><span style="color: #169179;"><strong style="color: #197841ff;"># Element row 2, column 3&nbsp;</strong></span><br /><strong><span style="color: #a35212ff;">print</span>("A[1,2] = ", A[<span style="color: #806800ff;">1</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">2</span>])</strong><br /><strong>print(<span style="color: #5a6464ff;">"---------------"</span>)</strong><br /><span style="color: #169179;"><strong style="color: #197841ff;"># If we want see ALL elements in the First row, we can do the following:</strong></span><br /><strong><span style="color: #a35212ff;">print</span>("A[0,:] = ", A[<span style="color: #806800ff;">0</span>,:])</strong><br /><strong><span style="color: #a35212ff;">print</span>(<span style="color: #5a6464ff;">"---------------"</span>)</strong><br /><span style="color: #169179;"><strong style="color: #197841ff;"># Similarly, if we wanted to see all ALL elements in the second column:</strong></span><br /><strong><span style="color: #a35212ff;">print</span>("A[:,1] = ", A[:,<span style="color: #806800ff;">1</span>])</strong><br /><strong><span style="color: #a35212ff;">print</span>(<span style="color: #5a6464ff;">"---------------"</span>)</strong><br /><span style="color: #169179;"><strong style="color: #197841ff;"># if we wanted to see All elements EXCEPT the first row:</strong></span><br /><strong><span style="color: #a35212ff;">print</span>("A[1:,:] = ", A[<span style="color: #806800ff;">1</span>:,])<br /><br /><span style="color: #197841ff;"># ALWAYS REMEMBER: PYTHON START INDEXING FROM 0 !!!</span></strong></pre>
        <p><span style="color: #e03e2d; font-size: 10pt;"><strong style="color: #c83223ff;">Out[1]:</strong></span></p>
        <pre><strong>A[1,2] = &nbsp;23</strong><br /><strong>---------------</strong><br /><strong>A[0,:] = &nbsp;[11 12 13 14]</strong><br /><strong>---------------</strong><br /><strong>A[:,1] = &nbsp;[12 22 32]</strong><br /><strong>---------------</strong><br /><strong>A[1:,:] = &nbsp;[[21 22 23 24]</strong><br /><strong>&nbsp;[31 32 33 34]]</strong></pre>
        <p>If we want to get a subset of a matrix, we can use the take( ) function to achieve it. Basically, we can take the columns or rows we want to keep, and assign them into a new matrix</p>
        <p><span style="color: #2dc26b; font-size: 10pt;"><strong style="color: #197841ff;">In[1]:</strong></span></p>
        <pre><strong><span style="color: #0000ff;">import</span> numpy <span style="color: #0000ff;">as</span> np<br /><span style="color: #197841ff;"># define a matrix first</span><br />A = np.array([[<span style="color: #806800ff;">11</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">12</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">13</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">14</span>],[<span style="color: #806800ff;">21</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">22</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">23</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">24</span>],[<span style="color: #806800ff;">31</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">32</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">33</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">34</span>]])<br /><span style="color: #a35212ff;">print</span>(A)<br />print(<span style="color: #5a6464ff;">"---------------"</span>)</strong><br /><strong><span style="color: #197841ff;"># let's try to remove the second column from matrix A<br /></span>B = A.take([<span style="color: #806800ff;">0</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">2</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">3</span>],axis=1)</strong><br /><strong><span style="color: #a35212ff;">print(</span>B)<br />print(<span style="color: #5a6464ff;">"---------------"</span>)</strong><br /><strong><span style="color: #197841ff;"># we can also remove the second row:<br /></span>C = A.take([<span style="color: #806800ff;">0</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">2</span>],axis=0)</strong><br /><strong><span style="color: #a35212ff;">print</span>(C)</strong><br /><br /></pre>
        <p><span style="color: #e03e2d; font-size: 10pt;"><strong style="color: #c83223ff;">Out[1]:</strong></span></p>
        <pre><strong>[[11 12 13 14]</strong><br /><strong>&nbsp;[21 22 23 24]</strong><br /><strong>&nbsp;[31 32 33 34]]</strong><br /><strong>---------------</strong><br /><strong>[[11 13 14]</strong><br /><strong>&nbsp;[21 23 24]</strong><br /><strong>&nbsp;[31 33 34]]</strong><br /><strong>---------------</strong><br /><strong>[[11 12 13 14]</strong><br /><strong>&nbsp;[31 32 33 34]]</strong></pre>
        <p>&nbsp;</p>
        <p>Another useful practice is to replace elements in a matrix based on certain conditions. We can use the condition as a logical statement in combination with the choose() function. Suppose I wanted to replace all the elements that are larger than 30 with the number 5. We can do the following:</p>
        <p><span style="color: #2dc26b; font-size: 10pt;"><strong style="color: #197841ff;">In[1]:</strong></span></p>
        <pre><strong><span style="color: #0000ff;">import</span> numpy <span style="color: #0000ff;">as</span> np<br /><span style="color: #197841ff;"># define a matrix first</span><br />A = np.array([[<span style="color: #806800ff;">11</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">12</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">13</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">14</span>],[<span style="color: #806800ff;">21</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">22</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">23</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">24</span>],[<span style="color: #806800ff;">31</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">32</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">33</span>,<span style="color: #806800ff;">34</span>]])<br /><span style="color: #a35212ff;">print</span>(A)<br />print(<span style="color: #5a6464ff;">"---------------"</span>)</strong><br /><strong><span style="color: #197841ff;"># let's replace elements that are larger than 30 with the number 5<br /></span>B =(A&gt;30).choose(A,5)</strong><br /><strong><span style="color: #a35212ff;">print(</span>B)</strong></pre>
        <p><span style="color: #e03e2d; font-size: 10pt;"><strong style="color: #c83223ff;">Out[1]:</strong></span></p>
        <pre><strong>[[11 12 13 14]</strong><br /><strong>&nbsp;[21 22 23 24]</strong><br /><strong>&nbsp;[31 32 33 34]]</strong><br /><strong>---------------</strong><br /><strong>[[11 12 13 14]</strong><br /><strong>&nbsp;[21 22 23 24]</strong><br /><strong>&nbsp;[ 5 &nbsp;5 &nbsp;5 &nbsp;5]]</strong></pre>
